The scavenger study was be used to propose the explicit mechanism of the composite catalyst. Superoxide, holes, and hydroxyl radicals are three forms of reactive species that a photocatalyst in an aqueous media produces when exposed to sunlight. These reactive species are what drive the organic molecules to photodegrade. Different active species numbers vary from system to system. Therefore, it is critical to confirm the existence and activity of active species in the photocatalytic system (Bhati et al., 2018; John et al., 1960). Chemicals that can capture and deactivate active species-known as scavengers-are typically added to the system in order to explore the role of active species. As scavengers, 1, 4-benzoquinone (BQ), EDTA, and isopropyl alcohol (IPA) were added, for holes, superoxide radicals, and hydroxyl radicals respectively. When the rate of degradation of TC was compared, it was discovered that EDTA > IPA > BQ. Hence it is concluded that the holes are the main active species driving the degradation of TC (Fig. 9
                           a). Fig. 9b shows the Tauc's plots ((αhυ)2 vs. hυ) the measured band gap for N-doped carbon dot was 1.67 eV. The photocatalytic process for TC degradation was improved by decreasing the band gap, particularly towards an effective visible light range. Charge carrying capacity of carbon dot was studied with Nyquist plot of electrochemical impedance spectroscopy. The semicircle's huge radius indicates low charge separation efficiency, low charge flow, and higher charge transfer resistance (Abraham et al., 2021). In the presence of TC the radius is reduced compared to bare N-doped carbon dot which indicate the better charge separation and flow with TC (Fig. 9c). Further amperometric technique was employed to study the activity of carbon dot and TC solution containing carbon dot upon light irradiation. Here the intensity of photocurrent of N-doped carbon dot gets enhanced in the presence of TC (Fig. 9d). It indicates that there is hype in the generation of charged particles in the solution with TC on irradiation which actively participated in the degradation process. All these observations support the ability of N-doped carbon dot to act as a photocatalyst for the degradation of TC under visible light irradiation. In addition to TC degradation, the photocatalytic activity of N-doped carbon dots in the presence of similar organic compounds like amoxicillin trihydrate (antibiotic), xylenol orange (dye), levofloxacin (antibiotic), and doxycycline (tetracycline antibiotic) was studied for 60 min (Fig. S11). The percentage degradation shows that doxycycline-a tetracycline antibiotic is undergoing degradation similar to TC. While levofloxacin degradation is 40.46%, amoxicillin trihydrate degradation exhibits the lowest degradation, 5%, and xylenol orange dye degradation is up to 20% over 60 min (Fig. 10
                           ).
